{
  "text": "To evaluate the sensitivity of the objective function to the model parameters, we perform the eigenvector/eigenvalue decomposition of the Hessian matrix [CITATION_1] for joint inversion of PP and PS data. Each component of an eigenvector (called the \"direction cosine\" and represented by the circles in Figure 2b ) indicates the relative sensitivity of the objective function to one of the model parameters. The gradient of the objective function is a linear combination of the eigenvectors weighted by the eigenvalues of the Hessian (Figure 2a) . Figure 2b displays the eigenvectors associated with the four largest eigenvalues. It shows that the objective function is most sensitive to the layer thickness D (and hence to V P0 because the vertical traveltimes are well constrained), followed by V S0 , V nmo;P , and V nmo;SV .",
